T1  - MAKING CARBON TAXATION A GENERATIONAL WIN WIN
AU  - Kotlikoff, Laurence
AU  - Kubler, Felix
AU  - Polbin, Andrey
AU  - Sachs, Jeffrey
AU  - Scheidegger, Simon
Y1  - 2021/02/01
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2021/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12483
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 3
EP  - 46
VL  - 62
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12483
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract Carbon taxation is mostly studied in social planner or infinitely lived-agent models, which obscure carbon taxation's potential to produce a generational win win. This article's large-scale, dynamic 55-period, overlapping generations model calculates the carbon tax policy delivering the highest uniform welfare gain to all current and future generations. Our model features coal, oil, and gas, increasing extraction costs, clean energy, technical and demographic change, and Nordhaus' carbon/temperature/damage functions. Assuming high-end carbon damages, the optimal carbon tax is $70, rising annually at 1.5%. This policy raises all generations' welfare by almost 5%. However, doing so requires major intergenerational redistribution.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - TRADE ASSOCIATIONS: WHY NOT CARTELS?
AU  - Levine, David K.
AU  - Mattozzi, Andrea
AU  - Modica, Salvatore
Y1  - 2021/02/01
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2021/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12487
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 47
EP  - 64
VL  - 62
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12487
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract The relevance of special interests lobbying in modern democracies can hardly be questioned. But if large trade associations can overcome the free riding problem and form effective lobbies, why do they not also threaten market competition by forming equally effective cartels? We argue that the key to understanding the difference lies in supply elasticity. The group discipline, which works in the case of lobbying, can be effective in sustaining a cartel only if increasing output is sufficiently costly?otherwise the incentive to deviate is too great. The theory helps organizing a number of stylized facts within a common framework.
ER  - 

